1558":"27 June 1558","1405":"1405","Smithfield, Middlesex, England (burned at the stake for Heresy)":"Smithfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Fleetwood, Lancashire, England":"Fleetwood, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roger De Holland was born in 1442, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas De Holland, was 38 and his mother, Mrs. Thomas De Holland, was 37. He married Alice FitzAlan in 1468, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 27 June 1558, in Smithfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 116."},"et":{"1442–27 June 1558":"1442–27. juuni 1558","1442–1558":"1442–1558","1448–1500":"1448–1500","1468–1520":"1468–1520","1468–Female":"1468–Surnud","1404–1460":"1404–1460","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1404":"1404","1448":"1448","1558":"1558","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1442":"1442","about 1468":"umbes 1468","1460":"1460","27 June 1558":"27. juuni 1558","1405":"1405","Smithfield, Middlesex, England (burned at the stake for Heresy)":"Smithfield, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fleetwood, Lancashire, England":"Fleetwood, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1442–27 June 1558":"1442–27. kesäkuuta 1558","1442–1558":"1442–1558","1448–1500":"1448–1500","1468–1520":"1468–1520","1468–Female"